item.title: Why do we have different blood types -- and do they make us more vulnerable to Covid-19?
item.description: Most humans fall into one of four blood groups — A, B, AB or O.

item.title: 'Science should not stand in the way' of opening schools, White House says
item.description: America's Covid-19 crisis is dire as 39 states see an increase in cases

item.title: Governor blame media for his state's Covid-19 response
item.description: CNN's Brianna Keilar points out the inaccuracies in Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis' argument that the media stopped asking about coronavirus in May and is to blame for the public becoming complacent and cases rising.

item.title: Even Donald Trump knows he's in deep, deep trouble
CEO's death and dismemberment sends shock waves through Nigeria's tech community
'Europe's last dictator' causes alarm at US State Department
item.description: The State Department expressed concern at crackdowns on protesters and journalists after two candidates opposing that country's leader -- nicknamed "Europe's last dictator" -- were disqualified from the race.

item.title: Before taking her own life, triathlete asked mother to 'lay bare the sins' of alleged abusers
item.description: He's a typically proud father as he recalls the joy of his daughter winning a medal.

item.title: Militant groups use murder, arson to enforce lockdown here
item.description: Armed groups in Colombia are using killings and other forms of violence to force civilians to follow their rules to slow coronavirus transmission, Human Rights Watch alleged on Wednesday.

item.title: Her husband strangled her. Then her country locked down and now she's forced to live with him
item.description: Activists in Mexico say lockdown measures put in place to slow the spread of Covid-19 lead to an uptick in domestic violence, especially against women. CNN's Matt Rivers reports.

item.title: Vogue's first Black editor-in-chief says he was racially profiled on his way into work
item.description: British Vogue's editor Edward Enninful said he was racially profiled on the way into work, with a security guard instructing him to enter the magazine's premises via the loading dock.

item.title: US-China relations are at an all time low, but Trump still seems unsure how to handle Beijing
Footage shows ships damaged by fire at Iranian port city
item.description: A fire has damaged at least seven vessels in a port city in Iran, acording to state media. Just two weeks after a fire at a nuclear complex, it's the latest in a series of mysterious incidents at key locations around the country. CNN's Jomana Karadsheh reports.

item.title: Ivanka Trump's alternative universe
item.description: In a week that has seen the President's daughter hawk beans on her social media account, and unveil a jobs assistance program in the midst of a global pandemic with the awkward moniker of "Find Something New," Ivanka Trump once again finds herself in the middle of a heap of criticism.

item.title: US has 'several' indications Iran has put portions of air defense on high alert
item.description: The US has "several" intelligence indications that Iran has put portions of its air defense system on "high alert" in recent days, following unexplained explosions at key facilities tied to the country's military and nuclear programs, according to a US official who is closely tracking developments.

item.title: How the world got Covid-19 messaging so wrong
Will Trump try to self-pardon?
item.description: President Donald Trump has used his pardon power sparingly, but overwhelmingly to benefit his friends and to protect his own interests. Former George W. Bush Administration official Jack Goldsmith recently analyzed Trump's pardons for Lawfare and concluded that "no president in American history comes close to matching Trump's systematically self-serving use of the pardon power."

item.title: How New Zealand became the apocalypse bunker of the world
item.description: In Queenstown — a picturesque ski spot that often attracts comparisons to Aspen, Colorado — rumors about foreigners investing in apocalypse-proof bunkers have been swirling for years.

item.title: Mary Trump's book breaks record with mammoth sales
item.description: Mary Trump's tell-all book had sold a staggering 950,000 copies by the end of its first day on sale, publisher Simon & Schuster said Thursday.

item.title: Bacteria that eats metal accidentally discovered by scientists
item.description: Scientists have discovered a type of bacteria that eats and gets its calories from metal, after suspecting they exist for more than a hundred years but never proving it.

item.title: Pentagon reveals some details of Trump's 'super duper' missile
item.description: Defense officials have revealed to CNN details about the hypersonic missile President Donald Trump has long touted as a "super duper" new military weapon -- part of a major effort to catch up to Russian and Chinese hypersonic weapons programs.

item.title: Covid-19 cases among US military causes mistrust in Okinawa
item.description: More US service members in Okinawa, Japan are testing positive for Covid-19, causing growing mistrust in an already troubled relationship between the two countries.

item.title: The county offering $3,000 if you contract Covid-19
The world loves the US dollar. Trump and the pandemic could change that
GOP state rep. claims Florida is doing 'just fine.' See CNN anchor read the stunning data to him
item.description: Florida Republican state lawmaker Rep. Anthony Sabatini, who has filed numerous lawsuits to prevent mask mandates in his state, tells CNN's Brianna Keilar that his state is doing just fine despite data showing Florida is a hotspot for coronavirus.

item.title: Plane flies Confederate flag over NASCAR race
item.description: A small plane flew a Confederate flag over the Bristol Motor Speedway on Wednesday as thousands of fans gathered to watch NASCAR's All-Star Race in Tennessee.

item.title: Dutch city cuts ties with Polish twin over 'LGBT-free zone'
item.description: A city in the Netherlands has severed ties with its sister city in Poland after the latter declared itself an "LGBT-free zone."

item.title: Zindzi Mandela tested positive for Covid-19 on the day she died, son says
item.description: Zindzi Mandela, South Africa's ambassador to Denmark and daughter of anti-apartheid leaders Nelson and Winnie Mandela, tested positive for Covid-19 on the day she died, her son Zondwa Mandela told South Africa's public broadcaster, SABC, Wednesday.

item.title: How masks are reshaping the face of the retail economy
item.description: As masks become ubiquitous amid the coronavirus pandemic, retailers are rushing to meet demand. CNN's Clare Sebastian reports.

item.title: One woman, four men, a tiny boat and a hungry polar bear
item.description: The summer before I turned 40 -- with my fertility ebbing, as everyone with a vested interest in such things felt the need to remind me -- I decided to set sail on the biggest adventure of my life.

item.title: The moon is about 85 million years younger than we thought, new study finds
item.description: The moon is a constant in our lives. It causes Earth's ocean tides to ebb and flow, it stabilizes the planet's axial tilt and, until recently, it was assumed to have accompanied the Earth for over 4.5 billion years.

item.title: CNN anchor tweets that he's still waiting for test results. His colleague responds
item.description: CNN reporters Fred Pleitgen and Victor Blackwell discuss the stark contrast of coronavirus testing in the US and Germany.

item.title: Teen reels in 700-pound bluefin tuna after 7-hour fight
item.description: Three teenage fishermen can tell their friends about the big one that didn't get away after fighting for 7 hours to land a huge bluefin tuna earlier this month off the coast of Maine.

item.title: What it means for Hong Kong as US revokes its special trade status
item.description: US President Donald Trump has signed an executive order ending Hong Kong's special trade status to treat the city the same as mainland China. He also signed the Hong Kong Autonomy Act into law to sanction businesses and individuals that help China restrict Hong Kong. CNN's Kristie Lu Stout reports.

item.title: 'Magic School Bus' author Joanna Cole dies age 75
item.description: Award-winning US author Joanna Cole, who wrote "The Magic School Bus" series and other children's books, has died at the age of 75.

item.title: Disappearing deep-sea, ultra-black fish mystery solved by scientists
item.description: The Invisible Man isn't the only expert in making himself imperceptible with optics science. Species of ultra-black fish also have that tactic down pat, according to a study published Thursday in the journal Current Biology.

item.title: Solar Orbiter mission shares closest images of the sun, reveals 'campfires' near its surface
item.description: Our sun was ready for its close-up last month, and the new Solar Orbiter mission captured the closest images ever taken of the sun during its first pass. The images were released on Thursday.

item.title: Chris Evans praises boy who saved sister from dog attack
item.description: Bridger Walker, a brave 6-year-old boy who shielded his sister from an attacking dog, received a surprise message from Chris Evans - who is sending Bridger a signed Captain America shield.

item.title: Elena Delle Donne 'shocked' her WNBA season medical opt-out request was denied, Mystics say she'll be paid
item.description: Elena Delle Donne, the reigning WNBA MVP, wants to play basketball.

item.title: Aggressive honey bees at Joshua Tree National Park force multiple campgrounds to close
item.description: Two areas of Joshua Tree National Park are closed after aggressive honey bees forced the park to clear the areas over the past week.

item.title: Cats may have been pets along the Silk Road over 1,000 years ago
item.description: Cats may have been pets for Kazakh pastoralists along the Silk Road over 1,000 years ago, a new study said.

item.title: This flying photographer is documenting how humans are impacting the planet
item.description: Flying hundreds of feet above the ground in a motorized paraglider, George Steinmetz has photographed the world's most remote environments from the sky.

item.title: Pandemic can't stop Simone Biles' stunning aerial display
item.description: US Olympic gymnast Simone Biles posted video of her performing a string of skills that she says she hadn't attempted since she was 13.

item.title: Morgues in hard-hit US states are filling up
item.description: With skyrocketing coronavirus hospitalizations in several states, hard-hit counties in Arizona and Texas are preparing for the worst by bringing in refrigerated trucks as morgues fill up.

item.title: What the heck is Georgia's governor doing?
item.description: On Wednesday in Georgia, there were almost 4,000 confirmed cases of coronavirus. Almost 2,800 people are hospitalized due to Covid-19, the highest number in the state's ongoing battle against the virus. A total of 37 people died, the highest number of daily deaths since June 25, according to data from the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.

item.title: Hospital owner allegedly faked thousands of Covid-19 tests
item.description: A hospital owner in Bangladesh was arrested Thursday on charges of fraud, after allegedly issuing thousands of fake Covid-19 test results to deceive patients out of an estimated $350,000, in a wide-ranging scam that has shaken confidence in the country's medical establishment.

item.title: Nobel laureates' controversial idea to speed up vaccine research
item.description: More than 100 top scientists including 15 Nobel laureates have written an open letter calling for volunteers to be exposed to the coronavirus to assist with vaccine development.

item.description: • Analysis: America was in need of a rallying cry. Then Trump stepped up to the mic • Trump and Fauci finally speak but Trump's attention remains elsewhere

item.title: Trump seems unsure how to handle Beijing
item.description: Throughout his time in office, US President Donald Trump has blown hot and cold on China.

item.title: A few tips to protect yourself online
item.description: CNN tech reporter Donie O'Sullivan thought he was being safe on social media. Watch social engineer & SocialProof Security CEO Rachel Tobac prove him very, very wrong.
